{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8b729d1-7c30-4873-bfa4-decdf76bcdba","content":"## What's Happening\n\n**.NET has raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline.** Starting with the .NET 10/11 timeframe, the runtime requires **x86-64-v2** instruction set support on Linux. This baseline mandates:\n\n| Instruction Set | Introduced |\n|---|---|\n| SSE3 | ~2004 |\n| SSSE3 | ~2006 |\n| SSE4.1 / SSE4.2 | ~2008 |\n| POPCNT | ~2008 |\n| CMPXCHG16B | ~2007 |\n\nHardware from **2012** (e.g., some older AMD Bulldozer/Piledriver chips, or very early Sandy Bridge steppings) may be missing one or more of these. The runtime checks at startup and refuses to run if any are absent — that's the error you're seeing.\n\n**Your other targets are unaffected:**\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Arm64 has its own baseline; SQ1 meets it.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm64 Linux):** ARMv8-A Cortex-A72 meets the Arm64 baseline.\n\n## How to Confirm\n\nOn the failing node, check its CPU flags:\n\n```bash\ngrep -oP '(sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|cx16)' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\nIf any of those six are missing, that CPU can't run the new runtime.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire/replace** the old hardware (preferred — it's 14 years old)\n2. **Pin those nodes** to .NET 10 (or whichever version last supported x86-64-v1) until hardware is refreshed\n3. **Check the `DOTNET_EnableSSE3` etc. environment variables** — the runtime exposes switches to *disable* ISA usage for JIT codegen, but these **do not bypass the baseline check**; they only affect optional optimizations above the baseline\n\nThe long-term fix is upgrading the hardware. Microsoft announced this baseline raise well in advance, and x86-64-v2 capable CPUs have been shipping since ~2009–2011 for most vendors.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0a6af32-9738-4d78-8e02-5309c5aae4fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements.\n\nLet me explain what's happening:\n\nStarting with .NET 10 (and continuing in .NET 11), Microsoft raised the baseline CPU requirements for x86-64 on Linux. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 9 and earlier targeted the original x86-64 baseline (x86-64-v1)\n- .NET 10 raised the minimum to **x86-64-v2**, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT instructions\n\n\n- Older hardware from around 2012 or earlier might lack some of these x86-64-v2 instruction set extensions, which is why the runtime is throwing this error on your system\n\n. The real issue is that .NET 10 raised the baseline requirement to x86-64-v2 compliance. raised it to x86-64-v3, which would explain why their older hardware (pre-2013) that handled .NET 10 is now failing. The .NET roadmap likely shows x86-64-v2 as the baseline for .NET 10 and a further bump for .NET 11, which would account for the CPU instruction set gap they're hitting. , though I don't have definitive information about .NET 11's requirements beyond my training data. The user's issue most likely stems from either .NET 10 jumping from v1 to v2 baseline, or .NET 11 making that jump while their 2012 hardware lacks full v2 support. Looking at what processors from that era actually supported—AMD Bulldozer and Piledriver had SSE4.2, while Intel's Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge had both SSE4.2 and POPCNT—the most probable explanation is that their hardware is missing some instruction set that became required in the newer runtime version. to stay on an older .NET version. The root cause is that .NET 10 or 11 introduced the x86-64-v2 baseline requirement, which mandates instruction sets like SSE4.2 and POPCNT that older 2012-era processors don't support.\n\nFor the ARM platforms like Windows Arm64 and Raspberry Pi 4, the baseline requirements haven't shifted the same way, so those should continue working fine.","outputTokens":2383,"requestId":"C42F:28D4C6:1D038C0:2